</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Scalable Electronic Phenotyping For Studying Patient Comorbidities</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ling%20AY"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Albee Y Ling</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3><span class="name western">Albee Y Ling</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Biomedical Informatics Training Program, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ling%20AY"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Albee Y Ling</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Alsentzer%20E"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Emily Alsentzer</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Emily Alsentzer</span>, <span class="degrees">MS</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Biomedical Informatics Training Program, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Alsentzer%20E"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Emily Alsentzer</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Chen%20J"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Josephine Chen</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3><span class="name western">Josephine Chen</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Biomedical Informatics Training Program, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Chen%20J"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Josephine Chen</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Banda%20JM"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id4"><span class="name western">Juan M Banda</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id4">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Juan M Banda</span>, <span class="degrees">PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Stanford Center for Biomedical Informatics Research, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Banda%20JM"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Juan M Banda</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Tamang%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id5"><span class="name western">Suzanne Tamang</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id5">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Suzanne Tamang</span>, <span class="degrees">PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>3</sup>Department of Biomedical Data Science, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Tamang%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Suzanne Tamang</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>3</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Minty%20E"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id6"><span class="name western">Evan Minty</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id6">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Evan Minty</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Biomedical Informatics Training Program, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Stanford Center for Biomedical Informatics Research, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Minty%20E"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Evan Minty</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>4</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="af1-2975685">
<sup>1</sup>Biomedical Informatics Training Program, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div id="af2-2975685">
<sup>2</sup>Stanford Center for Biomedical Informatics Research, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div id="af3-2975685">
<sup>3</sup>Department of Biomedical Data Science, Stanford University, Stanford, CA</div>
<div id="af4-2975685">
<sup>4</sup>Faculty of Medicine, University of Calgary, Calgary, AB, Canada</div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Collection date 2018.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div>©2018 AMIA - All rights reserved.</div>
<p>This is an Open Access article: verbatim copying and redistribution of this article are permitted in all media for any purpose</p>
<div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC6371288  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30815116/" class="usa-link">30815116</a>
</div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>Over 75 million Americans have multiple concurrent chronic conditions and medical decision making for these patients is mostly based on retrospective cohort studies. Current methods to generate cohorts of patients with comorbidities are neither scalable nor generalizable. We propose a supervised machine learning algorithm for learning comorbidity phenotypes without requiring manually created training sets. First, we generated myocardial infarction (MI) and type-2 diabetes (T2DM) patient cohorts using ICD9-based imperfectly labeled samples upon which LASSO logistic regression models were trained. Second, we assessed the effects of training sample size, inclusion of physician input, and inclusion of clinical text features on model performance. Using ICD9 codes as our labeling heuristic, we achieved comparable performance to models created using keywords as labeling heuristic. We found that expert input and higher training sample sizes could compensate for the lack of clinical text derived features. However, our best performing model included clinical text as features with a large training sample size.</p></section><section id="sec1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p>Approximately one in four adults have multiple chronic conditions, as do almost three in four adults aged 65 and older<sup><a href="#r1-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r1-2975685">1</a>-<a href="#r3-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r3-2975685">3</a></sup>. Patients with comorbidities are the major users of health care services, accounting for more than two-thirds of health care spending<sup><a href="#r4-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r4-2975685">4</a></sup>, yet limited evidence or guidance exists for clinical decision making for such patients<sup><a href="#r5-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r5-2975685">5</a></sup>. An important source of this evidence is retrospective observational studies, many of which rely on codified administrative data<sup><a href="#r6-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r6-2975685">6</a>-<a href="#r8-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r8-2975685">8</a></sup>. Comorbidity indices that attempt to control for confounding in observational studies are highly cited constructs despite the fact that administrative data have acknowledged limitations in such use cases<sup><a href="#r9-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r9-2975685">9</a></sup>. The electronic era in health care holds great promise for both individual and system level decision-making in complex patients with comorbidity. Expanding the feature set available for retrospective case detection through the electronic medical record (EMR) holds the potential to address some of these limitations of administrative data<sup><a href="#r10-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r10-2975685">10</a></sup>.</p>
<p>Current approaches to generating patient cohorts of specific medical conditions from EMR (also called EMR phenotyping) vary with respect to the degree of expert knowledge implicit in the phenotype definition, the feature engineering techniques employed, and the extent to which machine learning approaches are used<sup><a href="#r11-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2975685">11</a></sup>. Rule-based methods, such as those used in many of the phenotypes in the Phenotype Knowledge Base (PheKB),<sup><a href="#r12-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r12-2975685">12</a></sup> are disseminated as a set of requirements that are left to individual centers to implement against their unique data warehouse. They require expert input from physicians for development, and each method is specific to a given disease<sup><a href="#r13-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r13-2975685">13</a>,<a href="#r14-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r14-2975685">14</a></sup>. Recent studies in electronic phenotyping have demonstrated that using imperfectly labeled training examples as inputs for a statistical learning framework can produce models with comparable performance in substantially less time than rule based or supervised learning models<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a>,<a href="#r16-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r16-2975685">16</a></sup>. The imperfect labeling process assigns a selected sample as either a training case or control using a set of rules or heuristics, upon which machine learning models are trained. The creation of the keyword list needed to generate the labeling heuristic using clinical text requires clinical expertise, and variability in term usage across sites can produce different results. Furthermore, the approach needs features derived from clinical text via natural language processing (NLP) techniques, which vary among healthcare institutions and may not even be available at some locations<sup><a href="#r11-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r11-2975685">11</a></sup>.</p>
<p>Accumulated research experience using codified administrative health data for building patient cohorts and the study of comorbidity can be extended into an EMR based framework for noise tolerant machine learning. We developed a more scalable methodology for electronic phenotyping by leveraging both the widespread use of International Classification of Disease (ICD) codes in administrative data research and the development of the Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership (OMOP) Common Data Model (CDM) Version 5. Our approach for cohort building allows for generalization in three ways: (1) by using ICD9 codes for diseases, which are data elements accessible at almost any institution, as the basis of the imperfect labeling, (2) by modeling these approaches in the Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership common data model<sup><a href="#r17-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r17-2975685">17</a></sup>, such that the methods generalize to institutional members in the Observational Health Data Sciences and Informatics (OHDSI) consortium<sup><a href="#r18-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r18-2975685">18</a></sup>, and (3) by critically examining the trade-off between increasing labeling heuristic complexity and requirements of text-derived features against model performance and training sample size. By doing so, we hope to extend a cohort building and comorbidity modeling approach to healthcare institutions that may not have the capability to use textual sources for phenotyping.</p></section><section id="sec2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h2>
<section id="sec2_1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Phenotypes Studied</h3>
<p>To find the optimal phenotyping algorithm, we studied Myocardial Infarction (MI) and Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM), as the two diseases represent acute and chronic conditions, respectively. Rule-based definitions have been published for the two phenotypes, MI and T2DM, in Electronic Medical Records and Genomics (eMERGE) and OMOP initiatives, respectively. For eMERGE, a rule-based definition for the specific condition is developed by a partner institution in the form of pseudo-code for site-specific implementation, and iterative revisions and validations at other institutions result in the final definition. In OMOP, phenotypes or health outcomes of interest are defined by systematic review of published literature on the diagnostic criteria, validations studies, coding guidelines, and operational definitions for the phenotypes; the definitions are then applied to an observational database, the results validated, and the best practice queries are published.</p></section><section id="sec2_2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Data Description</h3>
<p>The patient dataset was extracted from the Stanford Clinical Data Warehouse (SCDW), which integrates data from Stanford Children’s Health (SCH) and Stanford Health Care (SHC)<sup><a href="#r19-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r19-2975685">19</a></sup>. The extract comprises 2 million patients, with an accompanying 27 million clinical notes. Our extract of patient data was from 1994 through 2014 and was stored in a structured and indexed form within a MySQL relational database in the ODHSI STRIDE 6 schema. STRIDE is the Stanford Translational Research Integrated Database Environment<sup><a href="#r19-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r19-2975685">19</a></sup>, and OHDSI, or Observational Health Data Sciences and Informatics, is an international consortium of academic and hospital centers around the world who are storing their health records in a common data model to develop open source methodologies and empower large-scale analytical efforts<sup><a href="#r18-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r18-2975685">18</a></sup>. The pre-processing steps to structure the data in the ODHSI schema included free text processing and mapping concepts to multiple medical ontology hierarchies<sup><a href="#r20-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r20-2975685">20</a>,<a href="#r21-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r21-2975685">21</a>,<a href="#r22-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r22-2975685">22</a></sup>.</p></section><section id="sec2_3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Model Framework</h3>
<p>We developed statistical classifiers of patients with T2DM and MI using the framework illustrated in <a href="#f1-2975685" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>. Training examples were noisily labeled using ICD9 codes in an L1 penalized (LASSO) logistic regression classifier.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f1-2975685"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 1.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=6371288_2975685f1.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/befe/6371288/6be925183113/2975685f1.jpg" loading="lazy" height="179" width="786" alt="Figure 1."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f1-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Full Model Framework. ICD9 codes were used to generate noisy labels, which were used as training examples in a LASSO logistic regression. The model labeled each patient as a case or control, which was validated against a gold standard clinician-reviewed dataset.</p></figcaption></figure><section id="sec2_3_1"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">ICD9 case definitions as a source of imperfect labels for phenotypes</h4>
<p>As the first step of creating our model, we used validated ICD9 administrative case definitions to create the noisy labels for MI and T2DM upon which our statistical classifiers were trained. For MI, we used OMOP’s “Broad definition with hospitalization” query for Acute Myocardial Infarction, which involves the following ICD9 codes: 410, 411.1, 411.8, and angina (413.9) during hospitalization (<a href="http://omop.org/HOI" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://omop.org/HOI</a>). For T2DM, we used the ICD9 codes mentioned as part of the multistep algorithm of the eMERGE definition in PheKB: 250.x0, 250.x2 (excluding 250.10, 250.12)<sup><a href="#r12-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r12-2975685">12</a></sup>. We used SQL to query the database to find all the patients with the appropriate ICD9 codes to designate as our initial noisy label cases and all other patients as controls. We then randomly selected the same number of adult cases and controls for subsequent model training.</p></section><section id="sec2_3_2"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Training a Statistical Classifier</h4>
<p>In creating our statistical classifier, we used Aphrodite, an R package<sup><a href="#r23-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r23-2975685">23</a></sup> that has functions for learning with a large number of imperfectly labeled samples to build phenotype classifiers. Features used were from the structured data of a patient record – prescriptions, laboratory test results, and diagnosis codes terms. Some of our classifiers include features from unstructured data, and terms were extracted from the unstructured data and normalized into concepts to reduce the total number of features and the number of correlated features<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a></sup>. Each feature was normalized by the number of measurement codes, as specified in<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a></sup>, features appearing in less than 2% of our training datasets were dropped. We then trained an L1 penalized logistic regression model for each phenotype using 5-fold cross-validation and the optimal model was chosen based on the area under the curve (AUC).</p></section><section id="sec2_3_3"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Incorporating Expert Review: Anchoring</h4>
<p>A framework developed by Halpern <em>et al</em>.<sup><a href="#r16-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r16-2975685">16</a></sup> provides an attractive data driven method for iterating the noisy label definition. They described an iterative process invoking an ‘expert in the loop’ in evaluating high ranking features from a regularized logistic regression model for possible ‘anchors’ that refine both the noisy label definition, and ultimately, the case definition. Anchors are posited to be highly specific pheno-markers, conditionally independent on the phenotype of interest.</p>
<p>We extended this feature evaluation to consider observables as candidates to be removed from the considered feature space. The selection of such features depended on an expert adjudicating that there was no biological or ‘medical practice’ basis for the observable to affect your prior for the phenotype of interest. In practice, we reviewed the full feature set for anchor candidates, and the top 50 features for features that could be removed.</p></section><section id="sec2_3_4"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Evaluation</h4>
<p>We applied our models to clinician-reviewed evaluation datasets for MI (94 cases and 94 controls) and T2DM (125 cases and 125 controls) and labeled every patient record as a case or control based on our learned model. The model assigned labels were compared to the clinician assigned label for each record in order to assess the model performance in terms of accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, and AUC. The gold standard chart review was conducted with the help of five clinicians according to the process described in the Agarwal <em>et al</em>.<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a></sup>. We also evaluated the performance of the ICD9 codes alone in labeling the gold standard data set in order to provide a reference for comparison. Finally, we assessed the performance of our classifier against the labeling process using keywords that was conducted by Agarwal et al. in order to determine how our model compares to existing methods.</p></section><section id="sec2_3_5"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Exploring Trade-Offs In Model Performance</h4>
<p>In order to maximize model performance while minimizing model complexity, we iteratively explored a range of options for the imperfect label assignment and feature engineering. Our exploration space consisted of three main directions (1) training sample size, (2) level of expert input, and (3) inclusion of text-derived features (<a href="#f2-2975685" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a>). We sought to determine how training sample size and expert input affect model performance and whether increasing the sample size and expert input introduced into a model without text-derived features could produce similar results to a model that uses clinical text features.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f2-2975685"><h5 class="obj_head">Figure 2.</h5>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/befe/6371288/23cc26a69620/2975685f2.jpg" loading="lazy" height="411" width="646" alt="Figure 2."></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f2-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Schematic showing the range of trade-offs that were explored to maximize model performance while minimizing model complexity.</p></figcaption></figure><p>We evaluated the impact of increasing training sample size by training our model with case and control sample sizes of 750 (750 cases and 750 controls respectively), 1,500, 2,068, and 5,000. A sample size of 2,068 was selected in recognition of the minimum labelling inaccuracy allowed (0.15). This is ½ of the sample size estimated for creating a logistic regression classifier with 5% generalization error, 95% of the time<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a>,<a href="#r24-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r24-2975685">24</a></sup>. Model performance might potentially be expected to asymptote beyond this limit. The four imperfectly labeled training sets of increasing size were used to fit a LASSO logistic regression models with and without the use of clinical text as features.</p>
<p>The impact of expert review on model performance was evaluated by comparing the performance of the standard models with models that incorporate the anchoring process described above. Both standard models and models with anchoring were built using LASSO logistic regression with and without the use of clinical text as features. These combinations allow for exploration of how expert input and the inclusion of text-derived features can together impact overall model performance. Finally, we assessed whether increasing sample size and/or expert input could produce similar results to a model with smaller sample size that utilizes text-derived features. We compared the results of a model with text-derived features and a sample size of 750 to a series of models without text-derived features with sample sizes of 1,500, 2,068, and 5,000 as well as a final model with a sample size of 5,000 that incorporates expert input via anchoring.</p></section></section></section><section id="sec3"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<section id="sec3_1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Performance Assessment Of Baseline Model</h3>
<p>We first developed a baseline model with training sample size of 750 that included clinical text as features but did not incorporate any expert input. This baseline model was most comparable to the previous model developed by Agarwal et al.<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a></sup> that used curated keywords to generate noisy labels. We evaluated the performance of our models against the models produced by Agarwal et al.<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a></sup> (<a href="#t1-2975685" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="t1-2975685"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 1:</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p>Imperfect labeling and model performance for phenotype T2DM. A) Evaluation of keywords and ICD9 derived labels on a gold standard evaluation set. B) Comparison of the models learned from keyword based labeling by Agarwal et al.<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a></sup> and our ICD9-based labeling, including clinical text as features. All models were learned with a sample size of n = 750.</p></div>
