</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/t1-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section><section id="sec3_2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Impact Of Training Sample Size On Model Performance</h3>
<p>We modulated the noisy label training sample size in order to determine whether increasing the number of noisy labels would improve performance of our T2DM model. <a href="#f3-2975685" class="usa-link">Figure 3</a> shows the accuracy of our model with increasing sample size applied to logistic regression with and without clinical text as features. When clinical text was used, accuracy increases marginally with sample size until levelling off at n= 2,068. When clinical text was not used, accuracy starts to stabilize starting from training sample size of 1,500. Similar trends on accuracy are observed in MI cohorts and the models without and with text stabilizes around 0.82 and 0.85 respectively. The AUCs for models without clinical text features are similar regardless of training sample size (AUCs = 0.92, 0.93, 0.92, and 0.93 for training sample sizes of 750, 1500, 2068, and 5,000 respectively). However, we observe an increase in AUCs for models with clinical text features with increasing training sample size (AUCs = 0.93, 0.95, and 0.96 for training sample sizes of 750, 1,500, and 2,068 respectively).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f3-2975685"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 3.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/befe/6371288/ecdf45806f39/2975685f3.jpg" loading="lazy" height="516" width="573" alt="Figure 3."></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f3-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Model accuracy as a function of increasing training sample size. Red corresponds to performance of the model with clinical text as features, and blue corresponds to performance of the model without clinical text as features.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="sec3_3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Impact Of Expert Input On Model Performance</h3>
<p>We also differentiated the complexity of our models by introducing an anchoring process implementing expert review to incorporate domain knowledge, similar to that implemented by Sontag <em>et al</em>.<sup><a href="#r16-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r16-2975685">16</a></sup>. Anchoring enables us to learn better noisy labels through successive iterations of the model (<a href="#f4-2975685" class="usa-link">Figure 4</a>). We evaluated classifier performance on models with and without anchoring as well as with and without clinical text as features.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f4-2975685"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 4.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/befe/6371288/5e585fbbac3e/2975685f4.jpg" loading="lazy" height="331" width="751" alt="Figure 4."></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f4-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Model iteration using feature anchoring and feature removal</p></figcaption></figure><p>When anchoring was performed on models without clinical text features, accuracy improved only when training sample size is large. The same accuracy was achieved (0.84) with and without expert input when n=750. However, accuracy increased from 0.86 to 0.90 when n=5,000. In terms of models with clinical text features, inclusion of physician anchoring process did not further improve the performance. A list of suggested anchors in models for T2DM can be seen in Supplemental <a href="#st1-2975685" class="usa-link">Tables 1</a> and <a href="#st2-2975685" class="usa-link">2</a>.</p>
