<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/st2-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section><section id="sec3_4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Achieving Comparable Model Performance Without Clinical Text As Features</h3>
<p>We further explored whether increasing the training sample size and expert input in the T2DM model could compensate for the lack of clinical text as logistic regression model features. When no anchoring was used, a model without clinical text as features can never perform as well as a model using clinical text. However, when anchoring was used with a training sample size of 5,000, the model without clinical text can outperform a model with clinical text using a training sample size of 750 (<a href="#f5-2975685" class="usa-link">Figure 5</a>).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f5-2975685"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 5.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=6371288_2975685f5.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/befe/6371288/df09313ba313/2975685f5.jpg" loading="lazy" height="272" width="703" alt="Figure 5."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f5-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Models without clinical text were evaluated to assess whether increasing the training sample size would allow for comparable performance in models with and without clinical text as features. When anchoring was added to the model with large training sample size (N=5,000) without clinical text, it could perform as well as a model using clinical text as features.</p></figcaption></figure></section></section><section id="sec4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p>Our work demonstrates the feasibility of using ICD9 codes to create noisy labeled training sets for electronic phenotyping models. As mentioned in Agarwal <em>et al</em>.<sup><a href="#r15-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r15-2975685">15</a></sup>, this learning framework enables efficient integration of various practice information (diagnoses, prescriptions, laboratory values, and clinical text extractions) in standardized terminology. Thus, it could serve as an alternative method of electronic phenotyping to rule-based definitions. Although we have achieved similar model performance compared to existing models using keywords as noisy labels, one advantage of using ICD9 codes as noisy labels is that it does not require the clinical expertise needed to curate keywords. In terms of features used in our models, we found that the inclusion of clinical text features greatly boosted performance. Interestingly, increasing training sample size only slightly improved model accuracy and the improvement is more noticeable when clinical text was used as features. However, the improvement ultimately approaches an asymptote at <em>n</em> = 2,068 and <em>n</em> = 1,500 with and without clinical text respectively, after which additional training data does not contribute much. We see a greater improvement in model accuracy as a function of sample size with the inclusion of clinical text, likely due to the availability of a wealth of additional features. In fact, a model generated with a sample size of n=2,068 or greater with clinical text yielded our best model for T2DM.</p>
<p>We further quantified the effects of having expert input via anchoring process on model performance. Although models that incorporate anchoring always yielded the same or better accuracy compared to their baseline counterparts, if coupled with a larger sample size they could outperform models with clinical text as features. One thing to be noted is that when including observations in LASSO logistic regression model, highly specific features from other tables may not be presented as anchor candidates. Future work could consider L2 penalized logistic regression to produce anchor suggestions and ensuring the domain expert is offered anchor candidates ranked from each available type of evidence (labs, drugs, diagnoses, and observations). Combining data from different observables in case definitions has been found to improve positive predictive value (PPV)<sup><a href="#r25-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r25-2975685">25</a></sup>.</p>
<p>One limitation of our study is that we have only applied our learning framework on two phenotypes, MI and T2DM. To demonstrate the generalizability of our model, additional work could be done to apply the same framework to widely accepted Charlson or Elixhauser comorbidities. We anticipate that the success in learning a model for any future phenotype would be predicated by the combination of ICD label accuracy and disease prevalence. In a study examining the accuracy of ICD definitions for Charlson and Elixhauser comorbidities relative to chart review, Quan <em>et al</em>. found that while the negative predictive value (NPV) of ICD labels across the Charlson and Elixhauser comorbidity set is high (mean 96.5% (standard deviation (SD) 3%))<sup><a href="#r26-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r26-2975685">26</a></sup>, the average PPV was a modest 77.1% (SD 17.5%). Hence, we would anticipate that label noise in controls would be low, but the noise would remain substantive in labelled cases, despite excellent specificity of ICD labels in these conditions (mean 99.2% SD 0.68%, <a href="#t2-2975685" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="t2-2975685"><h3 class="obj_head">Table 2:</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p>Descriptive statistics from the study by Quan <em>et al</em><sup><a href="#r26-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r26-2975685">26</a></sup>, comparing ICD codes (as assigned by professional coders) to chart abstraction across the conditions in Charlson and Elixhauser comorbidities.</p></div>
