</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/t2-2975685/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p>We would therefore make the following recommendations in carrying this work forward to other phenotypes, and for future work with the ones studied here when using ICD codes as noisy labels in training noise tolerant statistical classifiers: (1) Consider drawing training samples from clinical populations known to be enriched for the phenotype of interest. This could improve the PPV in labelled cases substantially, at an acknowledged risk of the model generalizability to other cases in the medical record. (2) Incorporate prevalence information into the modeling framework. This could be modeled as a Class Conditional Noise (CCN) learning problem, as recently addressed by Natarajan <em>et al</em>.<sup><a href="#r27-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r27-2975685">27</a></sup>. Their findings indicate that methods with weighted loss functions (such as weighted logistic regression) are provably noise-tolerant in the setting of CCN. Thus, prevalence information, if known <em>a priori,</em> could be incorporated as a set of weights in maximum likelihood estimation; if not known, these could be estimated in cross validation<sup><a href="#r27-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r27-2975685">27</a></sup>. In particular, Natarajan’s results indicate that they can achieve over 88% accuracy with CCN where up to 40% of the labels are corrupted. This compares favourably with the lowest PPV anticipated in our set of Elixhauser comorbidities of 56% (weight loss) and provides some confidence in the generalizability of this framework. (3) PPV in the positive class could be increased through iterative classification with learned models. In our study, an iteration was used to suggest anchor candidates, which were then used to relabel cases. However, the anchors <em>and</em> the learned model could be used to iteratively classify new training examples, producing a new set of noisy labels and further increasing the PPV for the labelled cases. (4) Given the low inter-observer agreement among domain experts who perform chart review illustrated in <a href="#t2-2975685" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>, it would be extremely helpful for future studies to quantify the time and efforts it will take in order to produce results that are consistent and reproducible.</p>
<p>It is worth noting that although we report accuracy as our main model performance statistics, these specific numeric values do not reflect the true accuracy of our model in a natural patient population. Measurements such as accuracy, PPV and NPV are highly dependent on the disease prevalence, which in our case is 50% since we had equal number of cases and controls in our training samples<sup><a href="#r28-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r28-2975685">28</a>,<a href="#r29-2975685" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r29-2975685">29</a></sup>. Thus, the accuracy, PPV, and NPV in a natural patient population will likely to differ from those measured as model performance. On the other hand, the values of sensitivity, specificity, and ROC measured in the statistical model are intrinsic properties of models and are not sensitive to disease prevalence. Future researchers should be cautious when using these measurements in evaluating model performance. Furthermore, once a given phenotype cohort is identified from a clinical data warehouse, there are other ways to evaluate the performance of our framework. The prevalence of each condition and their individual and combined predictive ability of adverse outcomes (e.g. mortality) are also meaningful ways to assess the value of using our proposed statistical model, compared to ICD9 codes alone in defining patient cohorts.</p></section><section id="sec5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h2>
<p>We demonstrated the feasibility of using ICD9 based creation of imperfectly labeled training sets for learning statistical classifiers of two common comorbid conditions. The universal attachment of ICD codes to episodes of care allows this approach to be widely used. Implementation in the OMOP CDM allows the framework to extend to other sites in the OHDSI network, which offers an opportunity not only to validate these models in risk adjustment, but develop new ones using statistical models of phenotypes and contribute to open source methods and knowledge base that are portable across institutions.</p></section><section id="sec6"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplemental Materials</h2></section><section id="ref-list1" class="ref-list"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">References</h2>
